                    "company": "Radboud University / Institute for Management Research",
                    "description": "The multidisciplinary research group Governance and Innovations in Social Services (GAINS) focuses on innovation in social services such as: healthcare, long term care, education, social housing, social welfare, and labour market integration. The common denominator of the services that they all intend to support citizens with socially recognized needs at various stages in their lives. Innovations are needed when these demands and needs change, when they are no longer met adequately by the services available, or when a more supportive context for innovations of services is required. In the GAINS program, social innovations are those innovations that respond to (new) societal demands and new social risks, and that traditionally have not been addressed by the market or existing institutions.\n\nGAINS recognizes that the search for innovations in the provision and delivery of social services has led to a growing interest in the governance of social services and a more \u2018customer\u2019 needed orientation of social services providers. Hence, the dual focus of the GAINS program is on the adoption and governance of innovations of social services and on innovations in the governance of social services.\n\nThe GAINS program focuses on a broad conceptualization of social innovation, including innovations in the governance, marketing, organization and management (service quality and co-creation) of social services. GAINS not only focuses on workplace innovations, but also on innovations in vocational training and development regimes and Human Resource Management and the governance infrastructures (including accountability regimes) that facilitate these workplace innovations by consolidation of experimentation, learning and adaptation.",
                    "title": "coordinator Governance and Innovations in Social Services",
                    "employment_type": null
                }
            ]
